In this paper, we present a novel domain adaptation framework for medical image segmentation, which addresses the problem of segmenting images from unseen domains. Our approach leverages a combination of domain-invariant feature learning and adversarial training to improve the generalization ability of deep neural networks to new domains. We demonstrate the effectiveness of our method on several benchmark datasets, including lung tumor segmentation, brain structure segmentation, and retinal vessel segmentation. Our experiments show that our proposed method outperforms existing state-of-the-art methods in terms of segmentation accuracy, especially when dealing with large domain shifts. Additionally, we perform an ablation study to analyze the contribution of each component of our framework, providing insights into the working mechanism of our approach. The main contributions of this work can be summarized as follows:

* A novel domain adaptation framework for medical image segmentation that combines domain-invariant feature learning and adversarial training;
* Experimental validation of the proposed method on several publically available datasets, demonstrating improved performance compared to state-of-the-art methods, especially when facing large domain shifts;
* An ablation study to investigate the effectiveness of different components of the proposed framework, providing valuable insights into its working mechanism.

Overall, our work has important implications for improving the robustness of deep learning models for medical image segmentation tasks, where domain shift is a common challenge due to variations in imaging protocols, patients, or diseases.

